, Lytham, Lancashire, England":"St Cuthbert's Church, Lytham, Lancashire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Woodplumpton, Preston, Lancashire, England":"Woodplumpton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Woodplumpton, Lancashire, England":"Woodplumpton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1129–1201":"about 1129–1201","1150–1206":"1150–1206","1175–1206":"1175–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1178–Female":"1178–Deceased","1181–Female":"1181–Deceased","1185–Female":"1185–Deceased","1201–Female":"1201–Deceased","1129–1201":"1129–1201","1175":"1175","Between 1189 and 1194":"from 1189 to 1194","1185":"1185","between 1189 and 1194":"from 1189 to 1194","1183":"1183","1150":"1150","1181":"1181","1170":"1170","1129":"1129","1206":"1206","about 1129":"about 1129","1201":"1201","1178":"1178","St. Cuthbert Cemetery, Lytham, Lancashire, England":"St Cuthbert's Church, Lytham, Lancashire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Woodplumpton, Preston, Lancashire, England":"Woodplumpton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Woodplumpton, Lancashire, England":"Woodplumpton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard FitzRoger of Woodplumpton was born about 1129, in Woodplumpton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. He married Margery de Banastre in 1183, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1201, in his hometown, at the age of 73, and was buried in St Cuthbert's Church, Lytham, Lancashire, England."},"et":{"about 1129–1201":"umbes 1129–1201","1150–1206":"1150–1206","1175–1206":"1175–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","1181–Female":"1181–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1201–Female":"1201–Surnud","1129–1201":"1129–1201","1175":"1175","Between 1189 and 1194":"1189 kuni 1194","1185":"1185","between 1189 and 1194":"1189 kuni 1194","1183":"1183","1150":"1150","1181":"1181","1170":"1170","1129":"1129","1206":"1206","about 1129":"umbes 1129","1201":"1201","1178":"1178","St. Cuthbert Cemetery, Lytham, Lancashire, England":"St Cuthbert's Church, Lytham, Lancashire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Woodplumpton, Preston, Lancashire, England":"Woodplumpton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Woodplumpton, Lancashire, England":"Woodplumpton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ab